%% Mikado graph for the 0.16.2 release — a DX patch surfaced by dogfooding
%% Bond on a real-world umbrella app (Photon, ~200+ modules).
%%
%% Arrows point from a goal to its prerequisites. Leaves (green) have no
%% further prerequisites and are safe to start with. Depth-first per Mikado:
%% pick a leaf, finish it, commit, repeat.
%%
%% Scope: four small code fixes plus two docs adds, all small and independent,
%% all unblocking real contract patterns that surfaced in Photon. Coheres
%% around "make assertion syntax less surprising and consumer-facing surfaces
%% better documented."
%%
%% Out of scope (deferred to 0.17.0 or later):
%%   - #2 wrapper-head shape leak. Real bug, but the right design (shape-
%%     neutral wrapper + restricted refs vs per-clause wrapper) is uncertain
%%     enough to warrant its own planning conversation.
%%   - #3 unused-variable warnings from destructure-in-head patterns. Partially
%%     subsumed by #2's resolution.
%%   - Uniform `Bond.CompileError` wrapper across all compiler parser errors.
%%     #6 narrowly targets the most common case; broader cleanup later.
%%
%% Findings (numbered as in the original dogfood report):
%%   1. Remote function calls (`String.starts_with?(x, "foo")`) reject the
%%      `Assertion.is_assertion_expression/1` guard because the AST's head is
%%      a `{:., _, _}` 3-tuple, not an atom. Relax the guard.
%%   4. `@doc` auto-emission on `defp` triggers Elixir's "@doc discarded for
%%      private functions" warning. Suppress at the `ContractDocs.doc_clauses/4`
%%      entry point.
%%   5. `@pre is_binary(x), positive: x > 0` parses as a 2-arg `@/2` call and
%%      falls through to Kernel's catch-all with an arity error. Detect at the
%%      `@` macro and raise a clear `CompileError`.
%%   6. `Assertion.new/5` failing the guard surfaces an unfriendly stack
%%      dumping the full `Macro.Env`. Wrap the macro-layer call sites in
%%      lib/bond.ex with a try/rescue that raises a Bond-shaped CompileError
%%      with file/line/source and a one-sentence diagnostic.
%%   7. `~>` and `<~` share precedence and left-associate, so
%%      `A ~> pattern <~ B` parses unintuitively. Pure docs add — short
%%      "Operator precedence" section in Bond.Predicates with the canonical
%%      example and parens fix.
%%   8. Telemetry metadata's `:function` key is `{name, arity}` — easy to
%%      forget when wiring handlers. Concrete metadata-map example in the
%%      Telemetry section so consumers don't have to read source.

flowchart TD
    G(["**Goal**<br/>0.16.2 — assertion ergonomics + DX patch (Photon-feedback)"])

    G --> S1[1. #1: relax is_assertion_expression for remote calls]
    G --> S2[2. #4: suppress @doc emission on defp]
    G --> S3[3. #5: clear error on bare+labelled mixed form]
    G --> S4[4. #6: friendly diagnostics on Assertion.new guard mismatch]
    G --> S5[5. #7: Predicates moduledoc — operator-precedence note]
    G --> S6[6. #8: Telemetry section — concrete metadata example]
    G --> D1[7. FAQ + assertion-syntax docs reflect #1's relaxation]
    G --> R1[8. CHANGELOG + 0.16.2 version bump]

    D1 --> S1
    R1 --> S1
    R1 --> S2
    R1 --> S3
    R1 --> S4
    R1 --> S5
    R1 --> S6
    R1 --> D1

    classDef leaf fill:#e7f5e7,stroke:#2e7d32,stroke-width:2px;
    class S1,S2,S3,S4,S5,S6 leaf;
